{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "These two operation modes can represent the summer and winter operating conditions of a DHS [27].",
    "Consequently, two data-based models are identified to form the ensemble.",
    "Note that monitoring techniques can be used to identify when such an ensemble is inadequate for modelling the real system, compensating by enlarging the ensemble with more models [26]; however, this is out of the scope of the current work.",
    "For the first working condition, a one-week input-output dataset D [1] is collected with a sampling time of τ = 5 minutes to identify model M [1], where the controllable supply temperature T s 0 is varied across its entire operating range using multilevel pseudorandom binary sequences (MPRBS) and the disturbances P c j, for j = 1,..., 5, follow typical profiles observed in DHSs [27], assumed to be measured during a specific season with thermal demand between 100 and 300 kW [26].",
    "A second one-week input-output dataset D [2] is then collected to identify model M [2], again varying T s 0 over its full range using MPRBS, while considering the disturbance profiles representative of a different season with thermal demand between 150 and 350 kW [26]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "These two operation modes can represent the summer and winter operating conditions of a DHS [27].",
    "Note that monitoring techniques can be used to identify when such an ensemble is inadequate for modelling the real system, compensating by enlarging the ensemble with more models [26]; however, this is out of the scope of the current work.",
    "For the first working condition, a one-week input-output dataset D [1] is collected with a sampling time of τ = 5 minutes to identify model M [1], where the controllable supply temperature T s 0 is varied across its entire operating range using multilevel pseudorandom binary sequences (MPRBS) and the disturbances P c j, for j = 1,..., 5, follow typical profiles observed in DHSs [27], assumed to be measured during a specific season with thermal demand between 100 and 300 kW [26].",
    "A second one-week input-output dataset D [2] is then collected to identify model M [2], again varying T s 0 over its full range using MPRBS, while considering the disturbance profiles representative of a different season with thermal demand between 150 and 350 kW [26]."
